`cluster-anlys` is a tool that constructs IP-transition graph (at basic block granularity) out of memory traces (output of MemGaze tool) and peforms Louvain clustering on that graph. 
The intuition is here is that, each cluster domain represents a "hot sequence", i.e., repeating series of memory operations which can be used to represent memory-intensive code regions.

MemGaze Pipeline:
1. <MEMGAZE_PATH>/install/bin/memgaze-inst <app>
2. <MEMGAZE_PATH>/install/bin/memgaze-run -p 100000 memgaze-<app>/<app>-memgaze
3. <MEMGAZE_PATH>/install/bin/memgaze-xtrace -i <app>-memgaze-trace-b8192-p100000/

Graph Cluster Analysis:
1. Get the trace file 
2. Generate basic-blocks.json file (scripts/ directory)
3. Place tracefile and basic-blocks.json in a directory
4. Run cluster analysis using `cluster-anlys` tool

Graph Semantics:
Node -> a basic block
Edge -> a trasition from a basic block to another (observed in trace)
Weight -> number of time that transition occured in trace

Useful commands:
- Mangling c++ function: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12400105/getting-mangled-name-from-demangled-name
  echo "int f1(char *, int) {} " | g++ -x c++ -S - -o- | grep "^_.*:$" | sed -e 's/:$//'
